    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i am studying for my civil eng exam and i'm a bit stuck on reinforced concrete. basically i get why concrete is good for compression but why do we actually need to add the steel rebar inside it?? like what is the actual relationship between the compressive strength of the concrete and the tensile strength of the steel in a foundation slab?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Reinforced concrete is a composite material because concrete is incredibly strong in compression but very weak in tension. Steel rebar is added specifically to counteract the tensile stresses that concrete cannot handle, which is crucial when a foundation slab is subjected to bending or pulling forces. The relationship is that the concrete handles the push (compression), while the steel handles the pull (tension), allowing the slab to resist bending moments effectively. This synergy is what gives the material its overall structural integrity.",
      "source": "target",
